# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: feature-store
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:feature-store/data-catalog] A **database catalog** of a database instance consists of metadata in which definitions of database objects such as base tables, views (virtual tables), synonyms, value ranges, indexes, users, and user groups are stored.
[src:feature-store/data-catalog] It is an architecture product that documents the database's content and data quality.
[src:feature-store/data-catalog] The SQL standard specifies a uniform means to access the catalog, called the INFORMATION_SCHEMA, but not all databases follow this, even if they implement other aspects of the SQL standard.
[src:feature-store/data-catalog] For an example of database-specific metadata access methods, see Oracle metadata.
[src:feature-store/feature-engineering] Beyond machine learning, the principles of feature engineering are applied in various scientific fields, including physics.
[src:feature-store/feature-engineering] For example, physicists construct dimensionless numbers such as the Reynolds number in fluid dynamics, the Nusselt number in heat transfer, and the Archimedes number in sedimentation.
[src:feature-store/feature-engineering] They also develop first approximations of solutions, such as analytical solutions for the strength of materials in mechanics.
[src:feature-store/feature-engineering] One of the applications of feature engineering has been clustering of feature-objects or sample-objects in a dataset.
[src:feature-store/feature-engineering] Especially, feature engineering based on matrix decomposition has been extensively used for data clustering under non-negativity constraints on the feature coefficients.
[src:feature-store/feature-engineering] These include *Non-Negative Matrix Factorization* (NMF), *Non-Negative Matrix-Tri Factorization* (NMTF), *Non-Negative Tensor Decomposition/Factorization* (NTF/NTD), etc.
[src:feature-store/feature-engineering] The non-negativity constraints on coefficients of the feature vectors mined by the above-stated algorithms yields a part-based representation, and different factor matrices exhibit natural clustering properties.
[src:feature-store/feature-engineering] Several extensions of the above-stated feature engineering methods have been reported in literature, including *orthogonality-constrained factorization* for hard clustering, and *manifold learning* to overcome inherent issues with these algorithms.
[src:feature-store/feature-engineering] Other classes of feature engineering algorithms include leveraging a common hidden structure across multiple inter-related datasets to obtain a consensus (common) clustering scheme.
[src:feature-store/feature-engineering] An example is *Multi-view Classification based on Consensus Matrix Decomposition* (MCMD), which mines a common clustering scheme across multiple datasets.
[src:feature-store/feature-engineering] Coupled matrix and tensor decompositions are popular in multi-view feature engineering.
[src:feature-store/feature-engineering] Feature engineering in machine learning and statistical modeling involves selecting, creating, transforming, and extracting data features.
[src:feature-store/feature-engineering] Even relatively insignificant features may contribute to a model.
[src:feature-store/feature-engineering] Feature selection can reduce the number of features to prevent a model from becoming too specific to the training data set (overfitting).
[src:feature-store/feature-engineering] Feature explosion occurs when the number of identified features is too large for effective model estimation or optimization.
[src:feature-store/feature-engineering] Feature explosion can be limited via techniques such as regularization, kernel methods, and feature selection.
[src:feature-store/feature-engineering] Automation of feature engineering is a research topic that dates back to the 1990s.
[src:feature-store/feature-engineering] Machine learning software that incorporates automated feature engineering has been commercially available since 2016.
[src:feature-store/feature-engineering] Multi-relational Decision Tree Learning (MRDTL) extends traditional decision tree methods to relational databases, handling complex data relationships across tables.
[src:feature-store/feature-engineering] It innovatively uses selection graphs as decision nodes, refined systematically until a specific termination criterion is reached.
[src:feature-store/feature-engineering] Most MRDTL studies base implementations on relational databases, which results in many redundant operations.
[src:feature-store/feature-engineering] These redundancies can be reduced by using techniques such as tuple id propagation.
[src:feature-store/feature-engineering] The deep feature synthesis (DFS) algorithm beat 615 of 906 human teams in a competition.
[src:feature-store/feature-engineering] The feature store is where the features are stored and organized for the explicit purpose of being used to either train models (by data scientists) or make predictions (by applications that have a trained model).
[src:feature-store/feature-engineering] A feature store includes the ability to store code used to generate features, apply the code to raw data, and serve those features to models upon request.
[src:feature-store/feature-engineering] Useful capabilities include feature versioning and policies governing the circumstances under which features can be used.
[src:feature-store/feature-engineering] Feature stores can be standalone software tools or built into machine learning platforms.
[src:feature-store/feature-engineering] Feature engineering can be a time-consuming and error-prone process, as it requires domain expertise and often involves trial and error.
[src:feature-store/feature-engineering] Deep learning algorithms may be used to process a large raw dataset without having to resort to feature engineering.
[src:feature-store/feature-engineering] However, deep learning algorithms still require careful preprocessing and cleaning of the input data.
[src:feature-store/feature-engineering] In addition, choosing the right architecture, hyperparameters, and optimization algorithm for a deep neural network can be a challenging and iterative process.
[src:feature-store/feature-store] A **feature store** is a centralized repository used in machine learning to store, manage, and serve features for model training and inference.
[src:feature-store/feature-store] It provides a unified interface for data scientists and engineers to access curated, reusable features derived from raw data, ensuring consistency between training and production environments.
[src:feature-store/feature-store] Feature stores typically support batch and real-time data pipelines, enabling efficient feature computation, storage, and retrieval at scale.
[src:feature-store/feature-store] Feature stores play a critical role in operationalizing machine learning systems by improving reproducibility, reducing data leakage, and promoting collaboration across teams.
[src:feature-store/feature-store] They often have features like feature versioning, metadata management, and access control that help keep data quality and governance high.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Statistics and mathematical optimisation methods compose the foundations of machine learning.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Data mining is a related field of study, focusing on exploratory data analysis (EDA) through unsupervised learning.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] From a theoretical viewpoint, probably approximately correct learning provides a mathematical and statistical framework for describing machine learning.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Most traditional machine learning and deep learning algorithms can be described as empirical risk minimisation under this framework.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] The term *machine learning* was coined in 1959 by Arthur Samuel, an IBM employee and pioneer in the field of computer gaming and artificial intelligence.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] The synonym *self-teaching computers* was also used during this time period.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] The earliest machine learning program was introduced in the 1950s, when Samuel invented a computer program that calculated the chance of winning in checkers for each side, but the history of machine learning is rooted in decades of efforts to study human cognitive processes.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] In 1949, Canadian psychologist Donald Hebb published the book *The Organization of Behavior*, in which he introduced a theoretical neural structure formed by certain interactions among nerve cells.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] The Hebbian theory of neuron interaction set the groundwork for how many machine learning algorithms work, with connected artificial neurons changing the strength of their connections based on data.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Other researchers who have studied human cognitive systems contributed to the modern machine learning technologies as well, including Walter Pitts and Warren McCulloch, who proposed the first mathematical model of neural networks including algorithms that mirror human thought processes.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] By the early 1960s, an experimental "learning machine" with punched tape memory, called Cybertron, had been developed by Raytheon Company to analyse sonar signals, electrocardiograms, and speech patterns using rudimentary reinforcement learning.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] It was repetitively "trained" by a human operator/teacher to recognise patterns and equipped with a "goof" button to cause it to reevaluate incorrect decisions.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] A representative book on research into machine learning during the 1960s was Nils Nilsson's book "Learning Machines", dealing mostly with machine learning for pattern classification.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Interest related to pattern recognition continued into the 1970s, as described by Duda and Hart in 1973.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] In 1981, a report was given on using teaching strategies so that an artificial neural network learns to recognise 40 characters (26 letters, 10 digits, and 4 special symbols) from a computer terminal.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] This follows Alan Turing's proposal in his paper "Computing Machinery and Intelligence", in which the question, "Can machines think?", is replaced by asking whether machines can convincingly imitate a human in its responses to human-posed questions.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] In 2014 Ian Goodfellow and others introduced generative adversarial networks (GANs) which could produce realistic synthetic data.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] By 2016 AlphaGo had won against top human players in Go using reinforcement learning techniques.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] As a scientific endeavour, machine learning grew out of the quest for artificial intelligence (AI).
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] In the early days of AI as an academic discipline, some researchers were interested in having machines learn from data.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] They attempted to approach the problem with various symbolic methods, as well as what were then termed "neural networks"; these were mostly perceptrons and other models that were later found to be reinventions of the generalised linear models of statistics.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Probabilistic reasoning was also employed, especially in automated medical diagnosis.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] However, an increasing emphasis on the logical, knowledge-based approach caused a rift between AI and machine learning.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Probabilistic systems were plagued by theoretical and practical problems of data acquisition and representation.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] By 1980, expert systems had come to dominate AI, and statistics was out of favour.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Work on symbolic/knowledge-based learning continued within AI, leading to inductive logic programming (ILP), but the more statistical line of research was now outside the field of AI proper, in pattern recognition and information retrieval.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Neural network research was abandoned by AI and computer science around the same time.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] This subfield, termed "connectionism", was continued by researchers from other disciplines, including John Hopfield, David Rumelhart, and Geoffrey Hinton.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Their main success came in the mid-1980s with the reinvention of backpropagation.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning (ML), reorganised and recognised as its own field, started to flourish in the 1990s.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] The field changed its goal from achieving artificial intelligence to tackling solvable problems of a practical nature.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] It shifted focus away from the symbolic approaches it had inherited from AI, and toward methods and models borrowed from statistics, fuzzy logic, and probability theory.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] There is a close connection between machine learning and compression.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] A system that predicts the posterior probabilities of a sequence given its entire history can be used for optimal data compression (by using arithmetic coding on the output distribution).
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Conversely, an optimal compressor can be used for prediction (by finding the symbol that compresses best, given the previous history).
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] This equivalence has been used as a justification for using data compression as a benchmark for "general intelligence".
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] An alternative view can show compression algorithms implicitly map strings into implicit feature space vectors, and compression-based similarity measures compute similarity within these feature spaces.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] For each compressor C(.) we define an associated vector space ℵ, such that C(.) maps an input string x, corresponding to the vector norm ||~x||.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] An exhaustive examination of the feature spaces underlying all compression algorithms is precluded by space; instead, feature vectors chooses to examine three representative lossless compression methods, LZW, LZ77, and PPM.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] According to AIXI theory, a connection more directly explained in Hutter Prize, the best possible compression of x is the smallest possible software that generates x.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] For example, in that model, a zip file's compressed size includes both the zip file and the unzipping software, since you can not unzip it without both, but there may be an even smaller combined form.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Examples of AI-powered audio/video compression software include NVIDIA Maxine, AIVC.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Examples of software that can perform AI-powered image compression include OpenCV, TensorFlow, MATLAB's Image Processing Toolbox (IPT) and High-Fidelity Generative Image Compression.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] In unsupervised machine learning, k-means clustering can be utilized to compress data by grouping similar data points into clusters.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] This technique simplifies handling extensive datasets that lack predefined labels and finds widespread use in fields such as image compression.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Data compression aims to reduce the size of data files, enhancing storage efficiency and speeding up data transmission.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] K-means clustering, an unsupervised machine learning algorithm, is employed to partition a dataset into a specified number of clusters, k, each represented by the centroid of its points.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] This process condenses extensive datasets into a more compact set of representative points.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Particularly beneficial in image and signal processing, k-means clustering aids in data reduction by replacing groups of data points with their centroids, thereby preserving the core information of the original data while significantly decreasing the required storage space.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Large language models (LLMs) are also efficient lossless data compressors on some data sets, as demonstrated by DeepMind's research with the Chinchilla 70B model.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Developed by DeepMind, Chinchilla 70B effectively compressed data, outperforming conventional methods such as Portable Network Graphics (PNG) for images and Free Lossless Audio Codec (FLAC) for audio.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] It achieved compression of image and audio data to 43.4% and 16.4% of their original sizes, respectively.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] There is, however, some reason to be concerned that the data set used for testing overlaps the LLM training data set, making it possible that the Chinchilla 70B model is only an efficient compression tool on data it has already been trained on.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Data mining uses many machine learning methods, but with different goals; on the other hand, machine learning also employs data mining methods as "unsupervised learning" or as a preprocessing step to improve learner accuracy.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Evaluated with respect to known knowledge, an uninformed (unsupervised) method will easily be outperformed by other supervised methods, while in a typical KDD task, supervised methods cannot be used due to the unavailability of training data.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning also has intimate ties to optimization: Many learning problems are formulated as minimisation of some loss function on a training set of examples.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Loss functions express the discrepancy between the predictions of the model being trained and the actual problem instances (for example, in classification, one wants to assign a label to instances, and models are trained to correctly predict the preassigned labels of a set of examples).
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Characterizing the generalisation of various learning algorithms is an active topic of current research, especially for deep learning algorithms.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning and statistics are closely related fields in terms of methods, but distinct in their principal goal: statistics draws population inferences from a sample, while machine learning finds generalisable predictive patterns.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Conventional statistical analyses require the a priori selection of a model most suitable for the study data set.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] In addition, only significant or theoretically relevant variables based on previous experience are included for analysis.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] In contrast, machine learning is not built on a pre-structured model; rather, the data shape the model by detecting underlying patterns.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] The more variables (input) used to train the model, the more accurate the ultimate model will be.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Leo Breiman distinguished two statistical modelling paradigms: the data model and the algorithmic model, wherein "algorithmic model" means more or less the machine learning algorithms like Random forest.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Some statisticians have adopted methods from machine learning, producing the field of *statistical learning*.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Analytical and computational techniques derived from deep-rooted physics of disordered systems can be extended to large-scale problems, including machine learning, e.g., to analyse the weight space of deep neural networks.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Statistical physics is thus finding applications in the area of medical diagnostics.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] A core objective of a learner is to generalise from its experience.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Generalisation in this context is the ability of a learning machine to perform accurately on new, unseen examples/tasks after having experienced a learning data set.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] The training examples come from some generally unknown probability distribution (considered representative of the space of occurrences) and the learner has to build a general model about this space that enables it to produce sufficiently accurate predictions in new cases.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] The computational analysis of machine learning algorithms and their performance is a branch of theoretical computer science known as computational learning theory.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] One major framework is the probably approximately correct learning model.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Because training sets are finite and the future is uncertain, learning theory usually does not yield guarantees of the performance of algorithms.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Instead, probabilistic bounds on the performance are quite common.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] The bias–variance decomposition is one way to quantify generalisation error.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] For the best performance in the context of generalisation, the complexity of the hypothesis should match the complexity of the function underlying the data.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] If the hypothesis is less complex than the function, then the model has underfitted the data.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] If the complexity of the model is increased in response, then the training error decreases.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] But if the hypothesis is too complex, then the model is subject to overfitting and generalisation will be poorer.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] In addition to performance bounds, learning theorists study the time complexity and feasibility of learning.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] In computational learning theory, a computation is considered feasible if it can be done in polynomial time.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] There are two kinds of time complexity results: Positive results show that a certain class of functions can be learned in polynomial time.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Negative results show that certain classes cannot be learned in polynomial time.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Although each algorithm has advantages and limitations, no single algorithm works for all problems.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Supervised learning algorithms build a mathematical model of a set of data that contains both the inputs and the desired outputs.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] The data, known as training data, consists of a set of training examples.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Each training example has one or more inputs and the desired output, also known as a supervisory signal.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] In the mathematical model, each training example is represented by an array or vector, sometimes called a feature vector, and the training data is represented by a matrix.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Through iterative optimisation of an objective function, supervised learning algorithms learn a function that can be used to predict the output associated with new inputs.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] An optimal function allows the algorithm to correctly determine the output for inputs that were not a part of the training data.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] An algorithm that improves the accuracy of its outputs or predictions over time is said to have learned to perform that task.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Types of supervised-learning algorithms include active learning, classification and regression.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Classification algorithms are used when the outputs are restricted to a limited set of values, while regression algorithms are used when the outputs can take any numerical value within a range.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] For example, in a classification algorithm that filters emails, the input is an incoming email, and the output is the folder in which to file the email.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] In contrast, regression is used for tasks such as predicting a person's height based on factors like age and genetics or forecasting future temperatures based on historical data.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Similarity learning is an area of supervised machine learning closely related to regression and classification, but the goal is to learn from examples using a similarity function that measures how similar or related two objects are.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] It has applications in ranking, recommendation systems, visual identity tracking, face verification, and speaker verification.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Unsupervised learning algorithms find structures in data that has not been labelled, classified or categorised.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Instead of responding to feedback, unsupervised learning algorithms identify commonalities in the data and react based on the presence or absence of such commonalities in each new piece of data.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Central applications of unsupervised machine learning include clustering, dimensionality reduction, and density estimation.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Cluster analysis is the assignment of a set of observations into subsets (called *clusters*) so that observations within the same cluster are similar according to one or more predesignated criteria, while observations drawn from different clusters are dissimilar.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Different clustering techniques make different assumptions on the structure of the data, often defined by some *similarity metric* and evaluated, for example, by *internal compactness*, or the similarity between members of the same cluster, and *separation*, the difference between clusters.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Other methods are based on *estimated density* and *graph connectivity*.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] A special type of unsupervised learning called self-supervised learning involves training a model by generating the supervisory signal from the data itself.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Dimensionality reduction is a process of reducing the number of random variables under consideration by obtaining a set of principal variables.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] In other words, it is a process of reducing the dimension of the feature set, also called the "number of features".
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Most of the dimensionality reduction techniques can be considered as either feature elimination or extraction.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] One of the popular methods of dimensionality reduction is principal component analysis (PCA).
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] PCA involves changing higher-dimensional data (e.g., 3D) to a smaller space (e.g., 2D).
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] The manifold hypothesis proposes that high-dimensional data sets lie along low-dimensional manifolds, and many dimensionality reduction techniques make this assumption, leading to the areas of manifold learning and manifold regularisation.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Semi-supervised learning falls between unsupervised learning (without any labelled training data) and supervised learning (with completely labelled training data).
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Some of the training examples are missing training labels, yet many machine-learning researchers have found that unlabelled data, when used in conjunction with a small amount of labelled data, can produce a considerable improvement in learning accuracy.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] In weakly supervised learning, the training labels are noisy, limited, or imprecise; however, these labels are often cheaper to obtain, resulting in larger effective training sets.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Reinforcement learning is an area of machine learning concerned with how software agents ought to take actions in an environment to maximise some notion of cumulative reward.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Due to its generality, the field is studied in many other disciplines, such as game theory, control theory, operations research, information theory, simulation-based optimisation, multi-agent systems, swarm intelligence, statistics and genetic algorithms.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] In reinforcement learning, the environment is typically represented as a Markov decision process (MDP).
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Many reinforcement learning algorithms use dynamic programming techniques.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Reinforcement learning algorithms do not assume knowledge of an exact mathematical model of the MDP and are used when exact models are infeasible.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Reinforcement learning algorithms are used in autonomous vehicles or in learning to play a game against a human opponent.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Other approaches have been developed which do not fit neatly into this three-fold categorisation, and sometimes more than one is used by the same machine learning system.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] For example, topic modelling, meta-learning.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Self-learning, as a machine learning paradigm, was introduced in 1982 along with a neural network capable of self-learning, named *crossbar adaptive array* (CAA).
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] It gives a solution to the problem learning without any external reward, by introducing emotion as an internal reward.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Emotion is used as a state evaluation of a self-learning agent.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] The CAA self-learning algorithm computes, in a crossbar fashion, both decisions about actions and emotions (feelings) about consequence situations.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] The system is driven by the interaction between cognition and emotion.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] It is a system with only one input, situation, and only one output, action (or behaviour) a.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] There is neither a separate reinforcement input nor an advice input from the environment.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] The backpropagated value (secondary reinforcement) is the emotion toward the consequence situation.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] The CAA exists in two environments, one is the behavioural environment where it behaves, and the other is the genetic environment, wherefrom it initially and only once receives initial emotions about situations to be encountered in the behavioural environment.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] After receiving the genome (species) vector from the genetic environment, the CAA learns a goal-seeking behaviour in an environment that contains both desirable and undesirable situations.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Several learning algorithms aim at discovering better representations of the inputs provided during training.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Classic examples include principal component analysis and cluster analysis.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Feature learning algorithms, also called representation learning algorithms, often attempt to preserve the information in their input but also transform it in a way that makes it useful, often as a pre-processing step before performing classification or predictions.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] This technique allows reconstruction of the inputs coming from the unknown data-generating distribution, while not being necessarily faithful to configurations that are implausible under that distribution.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] This replaces manual feature engineering, and allows a machine to both learn the features and use them to perform a specific task.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Feature learning can be either supervised or unsupervised.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] In supervised feature learning, features are learned using labelled input data.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Examples include artificial neural networks, multilayer perceptrons, and supervised dictionary learning.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] In unsupervised feature learning, features are learned with unlabelled input data.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Examples include dictionary learning, independent component analysis, autoencoders, matrix factorisation and various forms of clustering.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Manifold learning algorithms attempt to do so under the constraint that the learned representation is low-dimensional.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Sparse coding algorithms attempt to do so under the constraint that the learned representation is sparse, meaning that the mathematical model has many zeros.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Multilinear subspace learning algorithms aim to learn low-dimensional representations directly from tensor representations for multidimensional data, without reshaping them into higher-dimensional vectors.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Deep learning algorithms discover multiple levels of representation, or a hierarchy of features, with higher-level, more abstract features defined in terms of (or generating) lower-level features.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] It has been argued that an intelligent machine learns a representation that disentangles the underlying factors of variation that explain the observed data.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Feature learning is motivated by the fact that machine learning tasks such as classification often require input that is mathematically and computationally convenient to process.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] However, real-world data such as images, video, and sensory data have not yielded attempts to algorithmically define specific features.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] An alternative is to discover such features or representations through examination, without relying on explicit algorithms.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Sparse dictionary learning is a feature learning method where a training example is represented as a linear combination of basis functions and assumed to be a sparse matrix.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] The method is strongly NP-hard and difficult to solve approximately.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] A popular heuristic method for sparse dictionary learning is the *k*-SVD algorithm.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Sparse dictionary learning has been applied in several contexts.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] In classification, the problem is to determine the class to which a previously unseen training example belongs.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] For a dictionary where each class has already been built, a new training example is associated with the class that is best sparsely represented by the corresponding dictionary.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Sparse dictionary learning has also been applied in image denoising.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] The key idea is that a clean image patch can be sparsely represented by an image dictionary, but the noise cannot.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] In data mining, anomaly detection, also known as outlier detection, is the identification of rare items, events or observations that raise suspicions by differing significantly from the majority of the data.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Typically, the anomalous items represent an issue such as bank fraud, a structural defect, medical problems or errors in a text.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Anomalies are referred to as outliers, novelties, noise, deviations and exceptions.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] In particular, in the context of abuse and network intrusion detection, the interesting objects are often not rare, but unexpected bursts of inactivity.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] This pattern does not adhere to the common statistical definition of an outlier as a rare object.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Many outlier detection methods (in particular, unsupervised algorithms) will fail on such data unless aggregated appropriately.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Instead, a cluster analysis algorithm may be able to detect the micro-clusters formed by these patterns.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Three broad categories of anomaly detection techniques exist.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Unsupervised anomaly detection techniques detect anomalies in an unlabelled test data set under the assumption that the majority of the instances in the data set are normal, by looking for instances that seem to fit the least to the remainder of the data set.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Supervised anomaly detection techniques require a data set that has been labelled as "normal" and "abnormal" and involves training a classifier (the key difference from many other statistical classification problems is the inherently unbalanced nature of outlier detection).
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Semi-supervised anomaly detection techniques construct a model representing normal behaviour from a given normal training data set and then test the likelihood of a test instance being generated by the model.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Robot learning is inspired by a multitude of machine learning methods, starting from supervised learning, reinforcement learning, and finally meta-learning (e.g.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Association rule learning is a rule-based machine learning method for discovering relationships between variables in large databases.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] It is intended to identify strong rules discovered in databases using some measure of "interestingness".
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Rule-based machine learning is a general term for any machine learning method that identifies, learns, or evolves "rules" to store, manipulate or apply knowledge.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] The defining characteristic of a rule-based machine learning algorithm is the identification and utilisation of a set of relational rules that collectively represent the knowledge captured by the system.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] This is in contrast to other machine learning algorithms that commonly identify a singular model that can be universally applied to any instance in order to make a prediction.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Rule-based machine learning approaches include learning classifier systems, association rule learning, and artificial immune systems.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Based on the concept of strong rules, Rakesh Agrawal, Tomasz Imieliński and Arun Swami introduced association rules for discovering regularities between products in large-scale transaction data recorded by point-of-sale (POS) systems in supermarkets.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] For example, the rule $\{\mathrm {onions,potatoes} \}\Rightarrow \{\mathrm {burger} \}$ found in the sales data of a supermarket would indicate that if a customer buys onions and potatoes together, they are likely to also buy hamburger meat.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Such information can be used as the basis for decisions about marketing activities such as promotional pricing or product placements.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] In addition to market basket analysis, association rules are employed today in application areas including Web usage mining, intrusion detection, continuous production, and bioinformatics.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] In contrast with sequence mining, association rule learning typically does not consider the order of items either within a transaction or across transactions.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Learning classifier systems (LCS) are a family of rule-based machine learning algorithms that combine a discovery component, typically a genetic algorithm, with a learning component, performing either supervised learning, reinforcement learning, or unsupervised learning.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] They seek to identify a set of context-dependent rules that collectively store and apply knowledge in a piecewise manner to make predictions.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Inductive logic programming (ILP) is an approach to rule learning using logic programming as a uniform representation for input examples, background knowledge, and hypotheses.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Given an encoding of the known background knowledge and a set of examples represented as a logical database of facts, an ILP system will derive a hypothesized logic program that entails all positive and no negative examples.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Inductive programming is a related field that considers any kind of programming language for representing hypotheses (and not only logic programming), such as functional programs.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Inductive logic programming is particularly useful in bioinformatics and natural language processing.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Gordon Plotkin and Ehud Shapiro laid the initial theoretical foundation for inductive machine learning in a logical setting.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Shapiro built their first implementation (Model Inference System) in 1981: a Prolog program that inductively inferred logic programs from positive and negative examples.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] The term *inductive* here refers to philosophical induction, suggesting a theory to explain observed facts, rather than mathematical induction, proving a property for all members of a well-ordered set.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] A **machine learning model** is a type of mathematical model that, once "trained" on a given dataset, can be used to make predictions or classifications on new data.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] During training, a learning algorithm iteratively adjusts the model's internal parameters to minimise errors in its predictions.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] By extension, the term "model" can refer to several levels of specificity, from a general class of models and their associated learning algorithms to a fully trained model with all its internal parameters tuned.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Various types of models have been used and researched for machine learning systems, picking the best model for a task is called model selection.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Artificial neural networks (ANNs), or connectionist systems, are computing systems vaguely inspired by the biological neural networks that constitute animal brains.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Such systems "learn" to perform tasks by considering examples, generally without being programmed with any task-specific rules.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] An ANN is a model based on a collection of connected units or nodes called "artificial neurons", which loosely model the neurons in a biological brain.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Each connection, like the synapses in a biological brain, can transmit information, a "signal", from one artificial neuron to another.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] An artificial neuron that receives a signal can process it and then signal additional artificial neurons connected to it.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] In common ANN implementations, the signal at a connection between artificial neurons is a real number, and the output of each artificial neuron is computed by some non-linear function of the sum of its inputs.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] The connections between artificial neurons are called "edges".
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Artificial neurons and edges typically have a weight that adjusts as learning proceeds.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] The weight increases or decreases the strength of the signal at a connection.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Artificial neurons may have a threshold such that the signal is only sent if the aggregate signal crosses that threshold.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Typically, artificial neurons are aggregated into layers.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Different layers may perform different kinds of transformations on their inputs.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Signals travel from the first layer (the input layer) to the last layer (the output layer), possibly after traversing the layers multiple times.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] The original goal of the ANN approach was to solve problems in the same way that a human brain would.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] However, over time, attention moved to performing specific tasks, leading to deviations from biology.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Artificial neural networks have been used on a variety of tasks, including computer vision, speech recognition, machine translation, social network filtering, playing board and video games and medical diagnosis.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Deep learning consists of multiple hidden layers in an artificial neural network.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] This approach tries to model the way the human brain processes light and sound into vision and hearing.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Some successful applications of deep learning are computer vision and speech recognition.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Decision tree learning uses a decision tree as a predictive model to go from observations about an item (represented in the branches) to conclusions about the item's target value (represented in the leaves).
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] It is one of the predictive modelling approaches used in statistics, data mining, and machine learning.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Tree models where the target variable can take a discrete set of values are called classification trees; in these tree structures, leaves represent class labels, and branches represent conjunctions of features that lead to those class labels.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Decision trees where the target variable can take continuous values (typically real numbers) are called regression trees.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] In decision analysis, a decision tree can be used to visually and explicitly represent decisions and decision making.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] In data mining, a decision tree describes data, but the resulting classification tree can be an input for decision-making.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Random forest regression (RFR) falls under the umbrella of decision tree-based models.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] RFR is an ensemble learning method that builds multiple decision trees and averages their predictions to improve accuracy and to avoid overfitting.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] To build decision trees, RFR uses bootstrapped sampling; for instance, each decision tree is trained on random data from the training set.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] This random selection of RFR for training enables the model to reduce biased predictions and achieve a higher degree of accuracy.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] RFR generates independent decision trees, and it can work on single-output data as well as multiple regressor tasks.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] This makes RFR compatible to be use in various applications.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Support-vector machines (SVMs), also known as support-vector networks, are a set of related supervised learning methods used for classification and regression.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Given a set of training examples, each marked as belonging to one of two categories, an SVM training algorithm builds a model that predicts whether a new example falls into one category.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] An SVM training algorithm is a non-probabilistic, binary, linear classifier, although methods such as Platt scaling exist to use SVM in a probabilistic classification setting.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] In addition to performing linear classification, SVMs can efficiently perform a non-linear classification using what is called the kernel trick, implicitly mapping their inputs into high-dimensional feature spaces.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Regression analysis encompasses a large variety of statistical methods to estimate the relationship between input variables and their associated features.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Its most common form is linear regression, where a single line is drawn to best fit the given data according to a mathematical criterion such as ordinary least squares.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] The latter is often extended by regularisation methods to mitigate overfitting and bias, as in ridge regression.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Multivariate linear regression extends the concept of linear regression to handle multiple dependent variables simultaneously.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] This approach estimates the relationships between a set of input variables and several output variables by fitting a multidimensional linear model.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] It is particularly useful in scenarios where outputs are interdependent or share underlying patterns, such as predicting multiple economic indicators or reconstructing images, which are inherently multi-dimensional.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] A Bayesian network, belief network, or directed acyclic graphical model is a probabilistic graphical model that represents a set of random variables and their conditional independence with a directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] For example, a Bayesian network could represent the probabilistic relationships between diseases and symptoms.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Given symptoms, the network can be used to compute the probabilities of the presence of various diseases.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Efficient algorithms exist that perform inference and learning.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Bayesian networks that model sequences of variables, like speech signals or protein sequences, are called dynamic Bayesian networks.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Generalisations of Bayesian networks that can represent and solve decision problems under uncertainty are called influence diagrams.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] A Gaussian process is a stochastic process in which every finite collection of the random variables in the process has a multivariate normal distribution, and it relies on a pre-defined covariance function, or kernel, that models how pairs of points relate to each other depending on their locations.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Given a set of observed points, or input–output examples, the distribution of the (unobserved) output of a new point as a function of its input data can be directly computed by looking at the observed points and the covariances between those points and the new, unobserved point.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Gaussian processes are popular surrogate models in Bayesian optimisation used to do hyperparameter optimisation.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] A genetic algorithm (GA) is a search algorithm and heuristic technique that mimics the process of natural selection, using methods such as mutation and crossover to generate new genotypes in the hope of finding good solutions to a given problem.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] In machine learning, genetic algorithms were used in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Conversely, machine learning techniques have been used to improve the performance of genetic and evolutionary algorithms.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] The theory of belief functions, also referred to as evidence theory or Dempster–Shafer theory, is a general framework for reasoning with uncertainty, with understood connections to other frameworks such as probability, possibility and imprecise probability theories.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] These theoretical frameworks can be thought of as a kind of learner and have some analogous properties of how evidence is combined (e.g., Dempster's rule of combination), just like how in a pmf-based Bayesian approach would combine probabilities.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] However, there are many caveats to these beliefs functions when compared to Bayesian approaches to incorporate ignorance and uncertainty quantification.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] However, the computational complexity of these algorithms is dependent on the number of propositions (classes), and can lead to a much higher computation time when compared to other machine learning approaches.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Rule-based machine learning (RBML) is a branch of machine learning that automatically discovers and learns 'rules' from data.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] It provides interpretable models, making it useful for decision-making in fields like healthcare, fraud detection, and cybersecurity.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Key RBML techniques includes learning classifier systems, association rule learning, artificial immune systems, and other similar models.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] These methods extract patterns from data and evolve rules over time.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Typically, machine learning models require a high quantity of reliable data to perform accurate predictions.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] When training a machine learning model, machine learning engineers need to target and collect a large and representative sample of data.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Data from the training set can be as varied as a corpus of text, a collection of images, sensor data, and data collected from individual users of a service.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Overfitting is something to watch out for when training a machine learning model.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Trained models derived from biased or non-evaluated data can result in skewed or undesired predictions.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Biased models may result in detrimental outcomes, thereby furthering the negative impacts on society or objectives.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Algorithmic bias is a potential result of data not being fully prepared for training.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning ethics is becoming a field of study and, notably, becoming integrated within machine learning engineering teams.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Federated learning is an adapted form of distributed artificial intelligence to train machine learning models that decentralises the training process, allowing for users' privacy to be maintained by not needing to send their data to a centralised server.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] This also increases efficiency by decentralising the training process to many devices.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] For example, Gboard uses federated machine learning to train search query prediction models on users' mobile phones without having to send individual searches back to Google.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] In 2006, the media-services provider Netflix held the first "Netflix Prize" competition to find a program to better predict user preferences and improve the accuracy of its existing Cinematch movie recommendation algorithm by at least 10%.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] A joint team made up of researchers from AT&T Labs-Research in collaboration with the teams Big Chaos and Pragmatic Theory built an ensemble model to win the Grand Prize in 2009 for $1 million.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Shortly after the prize was awarded, Netflix realised that viewers' ratings were not the best indicators of their viewing patterns ("everything is a recommendation") and they changed their recommendation engine accordingly.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] In 2010, an article in *The Wall Street Journal* noted the use of machine learning by Rebellion Research to predict the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] In 2012, co-founder of Sun Microsystems, Vinod Khosla, predicted that 80% of medical doctors jobs would be lost in the next two decades to automated machine learning medical diagnostic software.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] In 2014, it was reported that a machine learning algorithm had been applied in the field of art history to study fine art paintings and that it may have revealed previously unrecognised influences among artists.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] In 2019 Springer Nature published the first research book created using machine learning.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] In 2020, machine learning technology was used to help make diagnoses and aid researchers in developing a cure for COVID-19.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning was recently applied to predict the pro-environmental behaviour of travellers.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Recently, machine learning technology was also applied to optimise smartphone's performance and thermal behaviour based on the user's interaction with the phone.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] When applied correctly, machine learning algorithms (MLAs) can utilise a wide range of company characteristics to predict stock returns without overfitting.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] By employing effective feature engineering and combining forecasts, MLAs can generate results that far surpass those obtained from basic linear techniques like OLS.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Recent advancements in machine learning have extended into the field of quantum chemistry, where novel algorithms now enable the prediction of solvent effects on chemical reactions, thereby offering new tools for chemists to tailor experimental conditions for optimal outcomes.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Machine Learning is becoming a useful tool to investigate and predict evacuation decision-making in large-scale and small-scale disasters.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Different solutions have been tested to predict if and when householders decide to evacuate during wildfires and hurricanes.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p01] Other applications have been focusing on pre evacuation decisions in building fires.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] Although machine learning has been transformative in some fields, machine-learning programs often fail to deliver expected results.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] Reasons for this are numerous: lack of (suitable) data, lack of access to the data, data bias, privacy problems, badly chosen tasks and algorithms, wrong tools and people, lack of resources, and evaluation problems.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] The "black box theory" poses another yet significant challenge.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] Black box refers to a situation where the algorithm producing an output is entirely opaque, meaning that even the designers of an application cannot audit the pattern that the machine extracted from the data.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] The House of Lords Select Committee, which claimed that such an "intelligence system" that could have a "substantial impact on an individual's life" would not be considered acceptable unless it provided "a full and satisfactory explanation for the decisions" it makes.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] In 2018, a self-driving car from Uber failed to detect a pedestrian, who was killed after a collision.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] Attempts to use machine learning in healthcare with the IBM Watson system failed to deliver even after years of time and billions of dollars invested.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] Microsoft's Bing Chat chatbot has been reported to produce hostile and offensive response against its users.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] Machine learning has been used as a strategy to update the evidence related to a systematic review and increased reviewer burden related to the growth of biomedical literature.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] While it has improved with training sets, it has not yet developed sufficiently to reduce the workload burden without limiting the necessary sensitivity for the findings research itself.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] Explainable AI (XAI), or Interpretable AI, or Explainable Machine Learning (XML), is artificial intelligence (AI) in which humans can understand the decisions or predictions made by the AI.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] It contrasts with the "black box" concept in machine learning where even its designers cannot explain why an AI arrived at a specific decision.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] By refining the mental models of users of AI-powered systems and dismantling their misconceptions, XAI promises to help users perform more effectively.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] XAI may be an implementation of the social right to explanation.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] Settling on a bad, overly complex theory gerrymandered to fit all the past training data is known as overfitting.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] Many systems attempt to reduce overfitting by rewarding a theory in accordance with how well it fits the data but penalising the theory in accordance with how complex the theory is.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] It is unclear to what extent the phenomenon threatens the long-term development of such models, and some techniques have been proposed to mitigate the effect.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] , inconsistent carriage lengths, unnatural amounts of visual noise, and a carriage bending along its length as it rounds the turn.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] In the field of artificial intelligence (AI), a hallucination or artificial hallucination (also called bullshitting, confabulation, or delusion) is a response generated by AI that contains false or misleading information presented as fact.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] The term draws a loose analogy with human psychology, where a hallucination typically involves false *percepts*.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] For example, a chatbot powered by large language models (LLMs), like ChatGPT, may embed plausible-sounding random falsehoods within its generated content.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] Detecting and mitigating errors and hallucinations pose significant challenges for practical deployment and reliability of LLMs in high-stakes scenarios, such as chip design, supply chain logistics, and medical diagnostics.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] Some software engineers and statisticians have criticized the specific term "AI hallucination" for unreasonably anthropomorphizing computers.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] Symbolic artificial intelligence models generally do not produce hallucinations, unlike large language models.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] Learners can also be disappointed by "learning the wrong lesson".
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] A toy example is that an image classifier trained only on pictures of brown horses and black cats might conclude that all brown patches are likely to be horses.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] Modifying these patterns on a legitimate image can result in "adversarial" images that the system misclassifies.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] Adversarial vulnerabilities can also result in nonlinear systems or from non-pattern perturbations.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] For some systems, it is possible to change the output by only changing a single adversarially chosen pixel.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] Machine learning models are often vulnerable to manipulation or evasion via adversarial machine learning.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] Researchers have demonstrated how backdoors can be placed undetectably into classifying (e.g., for categories "spam" and "not spam" of posts) machine learning models that are often developed or trained by third parties.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] Parties can change the classification of any input, including in cases for which a type of data/software transparency is provided, possibly including white-box access.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] Classification of machine learning models can be validated by accuracy estimation techniques like the holdout method, which splits the data into a training and test set (conventionally 2/3 training set and 1/3 test set designation) and evaluates the performance of the training model on the test set.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] In comparison, the K-fold-cross-validation method randomly partitions the data into K subsets and then K experiments are performed each considering 1 subset for evaluation and the remaining K-1 subsets for training the model.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] In addition to the holdout and cross-validation methods, bootstrap, which samples n instances with replacement from the dataset, can be used to assess model accuracy.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] In addition to overall accuracy, investigators frequently report sensitivity and specificity, meaning true positive rate (TPR) and true negative rate (TNR), respectively.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] Similarly, investigators sometimes report the false positive rate (FPR) as well as the false negative rate (FNR).
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] However, these rates are ratios that fail to reveal their numerators and denominators.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] Receiver operating characteristic (ROC), along with the accompanying Area Under the ROC Curve (AUC), offer additional tools for classification model assessment.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] Higher AUC is associated with a better performing model.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] The ethics of artificial intelligence covers a broad range of topics within AI that are considered to have particular ethical stakes.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] This includes algorithmic biases, fairness, accountability, transparency, privacy, and regulation, particularly where systems influence or automate human decision-making.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] Some application areas may also have particularly important ethical implications, like healthcare, education, criminal justice, or the military.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] Different machine learning approaches can suffer from different data biases.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] A machine learning system trained specifically on current customers may not be able to predict the needs of new customer groups that are not represented in the training data.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] When trained on human-made data, machine learning is likely to pick up the constitutional and unconscious biases already present in society.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] Systems that are trained on datasets collected with biases may exhibit these biases upon use (algorithmic bias), thus digitising cultural prejudices.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] For example, in 1988, the UK's Commission for Racial Equality found that St.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] George's Medical School had been using a computer program trained from data of previous admissions staff and this program had denied nearly 60 candidates who were found to either be women or have non-European-sounding names.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] Using job hiring data from a firm with racist hiring policies may lead to a machine learning system duplicating the bias by scoring job applicants by similarity to previous successful applicants.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] Another example includes predictive policing company Geolitica's predictive algorithm that resulted in "disproportionately high levels of over-policing in low-income and minority communities" after being trained with historical crime data.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] In fact, according to research carried out by the Computing Research Association in 2021, "female faculty make up just 16.1%" of all faculty members who focus on AI among several universities around the world.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] Furthermore, among the group of "new U.S. resident AI PhD graduates," 45% identified as white, 22.4% as Asian, 3.2% as Hispanic, and 2.4% as African American, which further demonstrates a lack of diversity in the field of AI.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] Language models learned from data have been shown to contain human-like biases.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] Because human languages contain biases, machines trained on language *corpora* will necessarily also learn these biases.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] In 2016, Microsoft tested Tay, a chatbot that learned from Twitter, and it quickly picked up racist and sexist language.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] In an experiment carried out by ProPublica, an investigative journalism organisation, a machine learning algorithm's insight into the recidivism rates among prisoners falsely flagged "black defendants high risk twice as often as white defendants".
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] In 2015, Google Photos once tagged a couple of black people as gorillas, which caused controversy.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] The gorilla label was subsequently removed, and in 2023, it still cannot recognise gorillas.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] Similar issues with recognising non-white people have been found in many other systems.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] Because of such challenges, the effective use of machine learning may take longer to be adopted in other domains.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] Concern for fairness in machine learning, that is, reducing bias in machine learning and propelling its use for human good, is increasingly expressed by artificial intelligence scientists, including Fei-Fei Li, who said that "[t]here's nothing artificial about AI.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] It's inspired by people, it's created by people, and—most importantly—it impacts people.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] There are concerns among health care professionals that these systems might not be designed in the public's interest but as income-generating machines.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] This is especially true in the United States, where there is a long-standing ethical dilemma of improving health care, but also increasing profits.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] For example, the algorithms could be designed to provide patients with unnecessary tests or medication in which the algorithm's proprietary owners hold stakes.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] There is potential for machine learning in health care to provide professionals with an additional tool to diagnose, medicate, and plan recovery paths for patients, but this requires these biases to be mitigated.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] Since the 2010s, advances in both machine learning algorithms and computer hardware have led to more efficient methods for training deep neural networks (a particular narrow subdomain of machine learning) that contain many layers of nonlinear hidden units.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] By 2019, graphics processing units (GPUs), often with AI-specific enhancements, had displaced CPUs as the dominant method of training large-scale commercial cloud AI.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] OpenAI estimated the hardware compute used in the largest deep learning projects from AlexNet (2012) to AlphaZero (2017), and found a 300,000-fold increase in the amount of compute required, with a doubling-time trendline of 3.4 months.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] Tensor Processing Units (TPUs) are specialised hardware accelerators developed by Google specifically for machine learning workloads.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] Unlike general-purpose GPUs and FPGAs, TPUs are optimised for tensor computations, making them particularly efficient for deep learning tasks such as training and inference.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] They are widely used in Google Cloud AI services and large-scale machine learning models like Google's DeepMind AlphaFold and large language models.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] TPUs leverage matrix multiplication units and high-bandwidth memory to accelerate computations while maintaining energy efficiency.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] Since their introduction in 2016, TPUs have become a key component of AI infrastructure, especially in cloud-based environments.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] Neuromorphic computing refers to a class of computing systems designed to emulate the structure and functionality of biological neural networks.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] These systems may be implemented through software-based simulations on conventional hardware or through specialised hardware architectures.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] A physical neural network is a specific type of neuromorphic hardware that relies on electrically adjustable materials, such as memristors, to emulate the function of neural synapses.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] The term "physical neural network" highlights the use of physical hardware for computation, as opposed to software-based implementations.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] It broadly refers to artificial neural networks that use materials with adjustable resistance to replicate neural synapses.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] Embedded machine learning is a sub-field of machine learning where models are deployed on embedded systems with limited computing resources, such as wearable computers, edge devices and microcontrollers.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] Running models directly on these devices eliminates the need to transfer and store data on cloud servers for further processing, thereby reducing the risk of data breaches, privacy leaks and theft of intellectual property, personal data and business secrets.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] Embedded machine learning can be achieved through various techniques, such as hardware acceleration, approximate computing, and model optimization.
[src:feature-store/machine-learning-p02] Common optimization techniques include pruning, quantisation, knowledge distillation, low-rank factorisation, network architecture search, and parameter sharing.
[src:feature-store/materialized-view] In computing, a **materialized view** is a database object that contains the results of a query.
[src:feature-store/materialized-view] For example, it may be a local copy of data located remotely, or may be a subset of the rows and/or columns of a table or join result, or may be a summary using an aggregate function.
[src:feature-store/materialized-view] The process of setting up a materialized view is sometimes called **materialization**.
[src:feature-store/materialized-view] This is a form of caching the results of a query, similar to memoization of the value of a function in functional languages, and it is sometimes described as a form of precomputation.
[src:feature-store/materialized-view] As with other forms of precomputation, database users typically use materialized views for performance reasons, i.e. as a form of optimization.
[src:feature-store/materialized-view] Materialized views that store data based on remote tables were also known as snapshots (deprecated Oracle terminology).
[src:feature-store/materialized-view] In any database management system following the relational model, a view is a virtual table representing the result of a database query.
[src:feature-store/materialized-view] Whenever a query or an update addresses an ordinary view's virtual table, the DBMS converts these into queries or updates against the underlying base tables.
[src:feature-store/materialized-view] A materialized view takes a different approach: the query result is cached as a concrete ("materialized") table (rather than a view as such) that may be updated from the original base tables from time to time.
[src:feature-store/materialized-view] This enables much more efficient access, at the cost of extra storage and of some data being potentially out-of-date.
[src:feature-store/materialized-view] Materialized views find use especially in data warehousing scenarios, where frequent queries of the actual base tables can be expensive.
[src:feature-store/materialized-view] In a materialized view, indexes can be built on any column.
[src:feature-store/materialized-view] In contrast, in a normal view, it's typically only possible to exploit indexes on columns that come directly from (or have a mapping to) indexed columns in the base tables; often this functionality is not offered at all.
[src:feature-store/materialized-view] Materialized views were implemented first by the Oracle Database: the Query rewrite feature was added from version 8i.
[src:feature-store/materialized-view] In PostgreSQL, version 9.3 and newer natively support materialized views.
[src:feature-store/materialized-view] In version 9.3, a materialized view is not auto-refreshed, and is populated only at time of creation (unless `WITH NO DATA` is used).
[src:feature-store/materialized-view] It may be refreshed later manually using `REFRESH MATERIALIZED VIEW`.
[src:feature-store/materialized-view] In version 9.4, the refresh may be concurrent with selects on the materialized view if `CONCURRENTLY` is used.
[src:feature-store/materialized-view] Microsoft SQL Server differs from other RDBMS by the way of implementing materialized view via a concept known as "Indexed Views".
[src:feature-store/materialized-view] The main difference is that such views do not require a refresh because they are in fact always synchronized to the original data of the tables that compound the view.
[src:feature-store/materialized-view] To achieve this, it is necessary that the lines of origin and destination are "deterministic" in their mapping, which limits the types of possible queries to do this.
[src:feature-store/materialized-view] This mechanism has been realised since the 2000 version of SQL Server.
[src:feature-store/materialized-view] Apache Kafka (since v0.10.2), Apache Spark (since v2.0), Apache Flink, Kinetica DB, Materialize, RisingWave, and Epsio all support materialized views on streams of data.
[src:feature-store/materialized-view] Materialized views are also supported in Sybase SQL Anywhere.
[src:feature-store/materialized-view] In IBM Db2, they are called "materialized query tables".
[src:feature-store/materialized-view] ClickHouse supports materialized views that automatically refresh on merges.
[src:feature-store/materialized-view] MySQL doesn't support materialized views natively, but workarounds can be implemented by using triggers or stored procedures or by using the open-source application Flexviews.
[src:feature-store/materialized-view] Materialized views can be implemented in Amazon DynamoDB using data modification events captured by DynamoDB Streams.
[src:feature-store/materialized-view] Google announced in 8 April 2020 the availability of materialized views for BigQuery as a beta release.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] As such, efforts to define, classify types, or structure metadata are expressed as examples in the context of its use.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] The term "metadata" has a history dating to the 1960s where it occurred in computer science and in popular culture.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Different types of metadata serve different functions.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] For example, descriptive metadata for a document might include the author, creation date, file size and keywords.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] It can help users find relevant information and discover resources.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] It can also help organize electronic resources, provide digital identification, and archive and preserve resources.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Metadata allows users to access resources by "allowing resources to be found by relevant criteria, identifying resources, bringing similar resources together, distinguishing dissimilar resources, and giving location information".
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Metadata of telecommunication activities including Internet traffic is very widely collected by various national governmental organizations.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] This data is used for the purposes of traffic analysis and can be used for mass surveillance.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Unique metadata standards exist for different disciplines (e.g., museum collections, digital audio files, websites, etc.).
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Describing the contents and context of data or data files increases its usefulness.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] For example, a web page may include metadata specifying what software language the page is written in (e.g., HTML), what tools were used to create it, what subjects the page is about, and where to find more information about the subject.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] This metadata can automatically improve the reader's experience and make it easier for users to find the web page online.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] A CD may include metadata providing information about the musicians, singers, and songwriters whose work appears on the disc.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] In many countries, government organizations routinely store metadata about emails, telephone calls, web pages, video traffic, IP connections, and cell phone locations.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Metadata is not strictly bound to one of these categories, as it can describe a piece of data in many other ways.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] While the metadata application is manifold, covering a large variety of fields, there are specialized and well-accepted models to specify types of metadata.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Bretherton & Singley (1994) distinguish between two distinct classes: structural/control metadata and guide metadata.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] *Structural metadata* describes the structure of database objects such as tables, columns, keys and indexes.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] *Guide metadata* helps humans find specific items and is usually expressed as a set of keywords in a natural language.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] According to Ralph Kimball, metadata can be divided into three categories: *technical metadata* (or internal metadata), *business metadata* (or external metadata), and *process metadata*.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Business metadata is important because it can greatly facilitate the usefulness of the data to business people.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] A simple example of business metadata is a glossary entry.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Hover functionality in an application or web form can enable a glossary definition to be shown when cursor is on a field or term.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Other examples of business metadata include annotation ability within applications.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] For example, a business user may be viewing a business intelligence (BI) report and notice a trend in the data.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] The user may have background knowledge as to why this trend occurs.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Some business intelligence tools enable the user to create an annotation within the report that explains the trend.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Such an annotation can enhance other users' understanding of the data.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] This example is especially powerful because it is created by a business user for the use of other business people.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] NISO distinguishes three types of metadata: descriptive, structural, and administrative.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] *Descriptive metadata* is typically used for discovery and identification, as information to search and locate an object, such as title, authors, subjects, keywords, and publisher.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] *Structural metadata* describes how the components of an object are organized.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] An example of structural metadata would be how pages are ordered to form chapters of a book.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Finally, *administrative metadata* gives information to help manage the source.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Administrative metadata refers to the technical information, such as file type, or when and how the file was created.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Two sub-types of administrative metadata are rights management metadata and preservation metadata.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] *Rights management metadata* explains intellectual property rights, while *preservation metadata* contains information to preserve and save a resource.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] An additional type of metadata beginning to be more developed is *accessibility metadata*.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Accessibility metadata is not a new concept to libraries; however, advances in universal design have raised its profile.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Projects like Cloud4All and GPII identified the lack of common terminologies and models to describe the needs and preferences of users and information that fits those needs as a major gap in providing universal access solutions.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Those types of information are accessibility metadata.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] The Schema.org website has incorporated several accessibility properties based on IMS Global Access for All Information Model Data Element Specification.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] While the efforts to describe and standardize the varied accessibility needs of information seekers are beginning to become more robust, their adoption into established metadata schemas has not been as developed.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] For example, while Dublin Core (DC)'s "audience" and MARC 21's "reading level" could be used to identify resources suitable for users with dyslexia and DC's "format" could be used to identify resources available in braille, audio, or large print formats, there is more work to be done.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Metadata was traditionally used in the card catalogs of libraries until the 1980s when libraries converted their catalog data to digital databases.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] In the 2000s, as data and information were increasingly stored digitally, this digital data was described using metadata standards.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] An early description of "meta data" for computer systems was written by David Griffel and Stuart McIntosh at the MIT Center for International Studies in 1967: "In summary then, we have statements in an object language about subject descriptions of data and token codes for the data.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Metadata is defined as the data providing information about one or more aspects of the data; it is used to summarize basic information about data that can make tracking and working with specific data easier.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] For example, a digital image may include metadata that describes the size of the image, its color depth, resolution, when it was created, the shutter speed, and other data.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] A text document's metadata may contain information about how long the document is, who the author is, when the document was written, and a short summary of the document.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Metadata within web pages can also contain descriptions of page content, as well as key words linked to the content.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] These links are often called "Metatags", which were used as the primary factor in determining order for a web search until the late 1990s.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] The reliance on metatags in web searches was decreased in the late 1990s because of "keyword stuffing", whereby metatags were being largely misused to trick search engines into thinking some websites had more relevance in the search than they really did.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Metadata can be stored and managed in a database, often called a metadata registry or metadata repository.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] However, without context and a point of reference, it might be impossible to identify metadata just by looking at it.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] For example: by itself, a database containing several numbers, all 13 digits long could be the results of calculations or a list of numbers to plug into an equation – without any other context, the numbers themselves can be perceived as the data.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] But if given the context that this database is a log of a book collection, those 13-digit numbers may now be identified as ISBNs – information that refers to the book, but is not itself the information within the book.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] The term "metadata" was coined in 1968 by Philip Bagley, in his book "Extension of Programming Language Concepts" where it is clear that he uses the term in the ISO 11179 "traditional" sense, which is "structural metadata" i.e.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] "data about the containers of data"; rather than the alternative sense "content about individual instances of data content" or metacontent, the type of data usually found in library catalogs.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Since then the fields of information management, information science, information technology, librarianship, and GIS have widely adopted the term.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] In these fields, the word *metadata* is defined as "data about data".
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] While this is the generally accepted definition, various disciplines have adopted their own more specific explanations and uses of the term.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Metadata (metacontent) or, more correctly, the vocabularies used to assemble metadata (metacontent) statements, is typically structured according to a standardized concept using a well-defined metadata scheme, including metadata standards and metadata models.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Tools such as controlled vocabularies, taxonomies, thesauri, data dictionaries, and metadata registries can be used to apply further standardization to the metadata.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Structural metadata commonality is also of paramount importance in data model development and in database design.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Metadata (metacontent) syntax refers to the rules created to structure the fields or elements of metadata (metacontent).
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] A single metadata scheme may be expressed in a number of different markup or programming languages, each of which requires a different syntax.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] For example, Dublin Core may be expressed in plain text, HTML, XML, and RDF.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] A common example of (guide) metacontent is the bibliographic classification, the subject, the Dewey Decimal class number.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] There is always an implied statement in any "classification" of some object.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] To classify an object as, for example, Dewey class number 514 (Topology) (i.e. books having the number 514 on their spine) the implied statement is: "<book><subject heading><514>".
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] This is a subject-predicate-object triple, or more importantly, a class-attribute-value triple.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] The first 2 elements of the triple (class, attribute) are pieces of some structural metadata having a defined semantic.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] The third element is a value, preferably from some controlled vocabulary, some reference (master) data.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] The combination of the metadata and master data elements results in a statement which is a metacontent statement i.e.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] All of these elements can be thought of as "vocabulary".
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Both metadata and master data are vocabularies that can be assembled into metacontent statements.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] There are many sources of these vocabularies, both meta and master data: UML, EDIFACT, XSD, Dewey/UDC/LoC, SKOS, ISO-25964, Pantone, Linnaean Binomial Nomenclature, etc.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] The process indexes pages and then matches text strings using its complex algorithm; there is no intelligence or "inferencing" occurring, just the illusion thereof.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Metadata schemata can be hierarchical in nature where relationships exist between metadata elements and elements are nested so that parent-child relationships exist between the elements.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] An example of a hierarchical metadata schema is the IEEE LOM schema, in which metadata elements may belong to a parent metadata element.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Metadata schemata can also be one-dimensional, or linear, where each element is completely discrete from other elements and classified according to one dimension only.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] An example of a linear metadata schema is the Dublin Core schema, which is one-dimensional.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Metadata schemata are often 2 dimensional, or planar, where each element is completely discrete from other elements but classified according to 2 orthogonal dimensions.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] The degree to which the data or metadata is structured is referred to as "granularity".
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] "Granularity" refers to how much detail is provided.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Metadata with a high granularity allows for deeper, more detailed, and more structured information and enables a greater level of technical manipulation.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] A lower level of granularity means that metadata can be created for considerably lower costs but will not provide as detailed information.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] The major impact of granularity is not only on creation and capture, but moreover on maintenance costs.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] As soon as the metadata structures become outdated, so too is the access to the referred data.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Hence granularity must take into account the effort to create the metadata as well as the effort to maintain it.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] In all cases where the metadata schemata exceed the planar depiction, some type of hypermapping is required to enable display and view of metadata according to chosen aspect and to serve special views.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Hypermapping frequently applies to layering of geographical and geological information overlays.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] International standards apply to metadata.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Much work is being accomplished in the national and international standards communities, especially ANSI (American National Standards Institute) and ISO (International Organization for Standardization) to reach a consensus on standardizing metadata and registries.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] The core metadata registry standard is ISO/IEC 11179 Metadata Registries (MDR), the framework for the standard is described in ISO/IEC 11179-1:2004.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] A new edition of Part 1 is in its final stage for publication in 2015 or early 2016.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] It has been revised to align with the current edition of Part 3, ISO/IEC 11179-3:2013 which extends the MDR to support the registration of Concept Systems.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] This standard specifies a schema for recording both the meaning and technical structure of the data for unambiguous usage by humans and computers.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] ISO/IEC 11179 standard refers to metadata as information objects about data, or "data about data".
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] In ISO/IEC 11179 Part-3, the information objects are data about Data Elements, Value Domains, and other reusable semantic and representational information objects that describe the meaning and technical details of a data item.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] This standard also prescribes the details for a metadata registry, and for registering and administering the information objects within a Metadata Registry.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] ISO/IEC 11179 Part 3 also has provisions for describing compound structures that are derivations of other data elements, for example through calculations, collections of one or more data elements, or other forms of derived data.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] This standard has become the general basis for other kinds of metadata registries, reusing and extending the registration and administration portion of the standard.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] The Geospatial community has a tradition of specialized geospatial metadata standards, particularly building on traditions of map- and image-libraries and catalogs.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Formal metadata is usually essential for geospatial data, as common text-processing approaches are not applicable.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] The Dublin Core metadata terms are a set of vocabulary terms that can be used to describe resources for the purposes of discovery.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] The W3C Data Catalog Vocabulary (DCAT) is an RDF vocabulary that supplements Dublin Core with classes for Dataset, Data Service, Catalog, and Catalog Record.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] DCAT also uses elements from FOAF, PROV-O, and OWL-Time.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] DCAT provides an RDF model to support the typical structure of a catalog that contains records, each describing a dataset or service.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Although not a standard, Microformat (also mentioned in the section metadata on the internet below) is a web-based approach to semantic markup which seeks to re-use existing HTML/XHTML tags to convey metadata.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Microformat follows XHTML and HTML standards but is not a standard in itself.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] In metadata, Naming and Design Rules are a set of guidelines and naming conventions that go beyond what a single data exchange standard specification will permit.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] The most common standard that Naming and Design Rules are created on is XML Schema.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] For example, the use of upper camel case data element names is a convention used in many standard but is not specified by the XML Schema specification.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Naming and Design Rules have become an important aspect of each organizations data exchange standards.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Within the United States, Naming and Design Rules standards are recommended for each federal and state agency.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Most common types of computer files can embed metadata, including documents, (e.g.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Microsoft Office files, OpenDocument files, PDF) images, (e.g.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Metadata may be added to files by users, but some metadata is often automatically added to files by authoring applications or by devices used to produce the files, without user intervention.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] While metadata in files are useful for finding them, they can be a privacy hazard when the files are shared.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Using metadata removal tools to clean files before sharing them can mitigate this risk.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Some metadata is created by the camera such as, color space, color channels, exposure time, and aperture (EXIF), while some is input by the photographer and/or software after downloading to a computer.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Most digital cameras write metadata about the model number, shutter speed, etc., and some enable you to edit it; this functionality has been available on most Nikon DSLRs since the Nikon D3, on most new Canon cameras since the Canon EOS 7D, and on most Pentax DSLRs since the Pentax K-3.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Metadata can be used to make organizing in post-production easier with the use of key-wording.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Filters can be used to analyze a specific set of photographs and create selections on criteria like rating or capture time.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] On devices with geolocation capabilities like GPS (smartphones in particular), the location the photo was taken from may also be included.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Photographic Metadata Standards are governed by organizations that develop the following standards.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Metadata is particularly useful in video, where information about its contents (such as transcripts of conversations and text descriptions of its scenes) is not directly understandable by a computer, but where an efficient search of the content is desirable.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] This is particularly useful in video applications such as Automatic Number Plate Recognition and Vehicle Recognition Identification software, wherein license plate data is saved and used to create reports and alerts.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Avid's MetaSync and Adobe's Bridge are examples of professional video editing software with access to metadata.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Various file systems are utilising metadata, such as FAT32 and NTFS.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Information on the times, origins and destinations of phone calls, electronic messages, instant messages, and other modes of telecommunication, as opposed to message content, is another form of metadata.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Geospatial metadata relates to Geographic Information Systems (GIS) files, maps, images, and other data that is location-based.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] Metadata is used in GIS to document the characteristics and attributes of geographic data, such as database files and data that is developed within a GIS.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p01] It includes details like who developed the data, when it was collected, how it was processed, and what formats it's available in, and then delivers the context for the data to be used effectively.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Metadata can be created either by automated information processing or by manual work.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Elementary metadata captured by computers can include information about when an object was created, who created it, when it was last updated, file size, and file extension.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] A metadata engine collects, stores and analyzes information about data and metadata in use within a domain.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Data virtualization emerged in the 2000s as the new software technology to complete the virtualization "stack" in the enterprise.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Metadata is used in data virtualization servers which are enterprise infrastructure components, alongside database and application servers.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Metadata in these servers is saved as persistent repository and describe business objects in various enterprise systems and applications.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Structural metadata commonality is also important to support data virtualization.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Standardization and harmonization work has brought advantages to industry efforts to build metadata systems in the statistical community.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Several metadata guidelines and standards such as the European Statistics Code of Practice and ISO 17369:2013 (Statistical Data and Metadata Exchange or SDMX) provide key principles for how businesses, government bodies, and other entities should manage statistical data and metadata.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Entities such as Eurostat, European System of Central Banks, and the U.S.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Environmental Protection Agency have implemented these and other such standards and guidelines with the goal of improving "efficiency when managing statistical business processes".
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Metadata has been used in various ways as a means of cataloging items in libraries in both digital and analog formats.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Such data helps classify, aggregate, identify, and locate a particular book, DVD, magazine, or any object a library might hold in its collection.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Until the 1980s, many library catalogs used 3x5 inch cards in file drawers to display a book's title, author, subject matter, and an abbreviated alpha-numeric string (call number) which indicated the physical location of the book within the library's shelves.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] The Dewey Decimal System employed by libraries for the classification of library materials by subject is an early example of metadata usage.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] The early paper catalog had information regarding whichever item was described on said card: title, author, subject, and a number as to where to find said item.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Beginning in the 1980s and 1990s, many libraries replaced these paper file cards with computer databases.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] These computer databases make it much easier and faster for users to do keyword searches.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Another form of older metadata collection is the use by the US Census Bureau of what is known as the "Long Form".
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] The Long Form asks questions that are used to create demographic data to find patterns of distribution.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Libraries employ metadata in library catalogues, most commonly as part of an Integrated Library Management System.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Metadata is obtained by cataloging resources such as books, periodicals, DVDs, web pages or digital images.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] This data is stored in the integrated library management system, ILMS, using the MARC metadata standard.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] The purpose is to direct patrons to the physical or electronic location of items or areas they seek as well as to provide a description of the item/s in question.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] More recent and specialized instances of library metadata include the establishment of digital libraries including e-print repositories and digital image libraries.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] While often based on library principles, the focus on non-librarian use, especially in providing metadata, means they do not follow traditional or common cataloging approaches.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Given the custom nature of included materials, metadata fields are often specially created e.g. taxonomic classification fields, location fields, keywords, or copyright statement.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Standard file information such as file size and format are usually automatically included.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Library operation has for decades been a key topic in efforts toward international standardization.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Standards for metadata in digital libraries include Dublin Core, METS, MODS, DDI, DOI, URN, PREMIS schema, EML, and OAI-PMH.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Leading libraries in the world give hints on their metadata standards strategies.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] A similar concept is the synset, short for *synonym set*, a group of one or more synonyms that share a common meaning in some context.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Synsets are a fundamental concept in computational linguistics and lexical semantics, most notably used in the WordNet lexical database of English.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] The concept has been extended to other languages and multilingual projects such as EuroWordNet, BabelNet, and the Global WordNet initiative.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Metadata for scientific publications is often created by journal publishers and citation databases such as PubMed and Web of Science.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] The data contained within manuscripts or accompanying them as supplementary material is less often subject to metadata creation, though they may be submitted to e.g. biomedical databases after publication.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] The original authors and database curators then become responsible for metadata creation, with the assistance of automated processes.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Comprehensive metadata for all experimental data is the foundation of the FAIR Guiding Principles, or the standards for ensuring research data are findable, accessible, interoperable, and reusable.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Such metadata can then be utilized, complemented, and made accessible in useful ways.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] OpenAlex is a free online index of over 200 million scientific documents that integrates and provides metadata such as sources, citations, author information, scientific fields, and research topics.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Its API and open source website can be used for metascience, scientometrics, and novel tools that query this semantic web of papers.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Another project under development, Scholia, uses the metadata of scientific publications for various visualizations and aggregation features such as providing a simple user interface summarizing literature about a specific feature of the SARS-CoV-2 virus using Wikidata's "main subject" property.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] In research labor, transparent metadata about authors' contributions to works have been proposed – e.g. the role played in the production of the paper, the level of contribution and the responsibilities.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Moreover, various metadata about scientific outputs can be created or complemented – for instance, some organizations attempt to track and link citations of papers as 'Supporting', 'Mentioning' or 'Contrasting' the study.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Metadata in a museum context is the information that trained cultural documentation specialists, such as archivists, librarians, museum registrars and curators, create to index, structure, describe, identify, or otherwise specify works of art, architecture, cultural objects and their images.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Descriptive metadata is most commonly used in museum contexts for object identification and resource recovery purposes.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Many museums and cultural heritage centers recognize that given the diversity of artworks and cultural objects, no single model or standard suffices to describe and catalog cultural works.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] For example, a sculpted Indigenous artifact could be classified as an artwork, an archaeological artifact, or an Indigenous heritage item.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] These standards use HTML and XML markup languages for machine processing, publication and implementation.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] The Anglo-American Cataloguing Rules (AACR), originally developed for characterizing books, have also been applied to cultural objects, works of art and architecture.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Standards, such as the CCO, are integrated within a Museum's Collections Management System (CMS), a database through which museums are able to manage their collections, acquisitions, loans and conservation.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Scholars and professionals in the field note that the "quickly evolving landscape of standards and technologies" creates challenges for cultural documentarians, specifically non-technically trained professionals.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Most collecting institutions and museums use a relational database to categorize cultural works and their images.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Relational databases and metadata work to document and describe the complex relationships amongst cultural objects and multi-faceted works of art, as well as between objects and places, people, and artistic movements.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Relational database structures are also beneficial within collecting institutions and museums because they allow for archivists to make a clear distinction between cultural objects and their images; an unclear distinction could lead to confusing and inaccurate searches.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] The established institutional cataloging practices, goals, and expertise of cultural documentarians and database structure also influence the information ascribed to cultural objects and the ways in which cultural objects are categorized.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Additionally, museums often employ standardized commercial collection management software that prescribes and limits the ways in which archivists can describe artworks and cultural objects.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] As well, collecting institutions and museums use Controlled Vocabularies to describe cultural objects and artworks in their collections.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Getty Vocabularies and the Library of Congress Controlled Vocabularies are reputable within the museum community and are recommended by CCO standards.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Museums are encouraged to use controlled vocabularies that are contextual and relevant to their collections and enhance the functionality of their digital information systems.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Controlled Vocabularies are beneficial within databases because they provide a high level of consistency, improving resource retrieval.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Metadata structures, including controlled vocabularies, reflect the ontologies of the systems from which they were created.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Often the processes through which cultural objects are described and categorized through metadata in museums do not reflect the perspectives of the maker communities.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Metadata has been instrumental in the creation of digital information systems and archives within museums and has made it easier for museums to publish digital content online.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] This has enabled audiences who might not have had access to cultural objects due to geographic or economic barriers to have access to them.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] In the 2000s, as more museums have adopted archival standards and created intricate databases, discussions about Linked Data between museum databases have come up in the museum, archival, and library science communities.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Collection Management Systems (CMS) and Digital Asset Management tools can be local or shared systems.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Digital Humanities scholars note many benefits of interoperability between museum databases and collections, while also acknowledging the difficulties of achieving such interoperability.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Problems involving metadata in litigation in the United States are becoming widespread.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Courts have looked at various questions involving metadata, including the discoverability of metadata by parties.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] The Federal Rules of Civil Procedure have specific rules for discovery of electronically stored information, and subsequent case law applying those rules has elucidated on the litigant's duty to produce metadata when litigating in federal court.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] In October 2009, the Arizona Supreme Court has ruled that metadata records are public record.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Document metadata have proven particularly important in legal environments in which litigation has requested metadata, that can include sensitive information detrimental to a certain party in court.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Using metadata removal tools to "clean" or redact documents can mitigate the risks of unwittingly sending sensitive data.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] This process partially (see data remanence) protects law firms from potentially damaging leaking of sensitive data through electronic discovery.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Opinion polls have shown that 45% of Americans are "not at all confident" in the ability of social media sites to ensure their personal data is secure and 40% say that social media sites should not be able to store any information on individuals.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] 76% of Americans say that they are not confident that the information advertising agencies collect on them is secure and 50% say that online advertising agencies should not be allowed to record any of their information at all.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] In the EU, the Snowden disclosures have been influential in its review of matters concerning privacy and the processing of personal data.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] As of 2025, of the 18 European countries surveyed by the Data Retention Directive, only Germany, the Netherlands and Romania do not have any data retention rules in force.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] On 6 October 2020, the Court of Justice for the European Union (CJEU) ruled that indiscriminate mass data retention schemes are illegal under EU law.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] With France passing a law on 18 December 2013 that facilitates the collection of data by the French military and intelligence services.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] While in April 2022 the Portuguese Constitutional Court declared unconstitutional the CJEU laws on the retention of data generated or processed in connection with the provision of publicly available electronic communications services or of public communications networks.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] In Australia, the need to strengthen national security has resulted in the introduction of a new metadata storage law.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] This new law means that both security and policing agencies will be allowed to access up to 2 years of an individual's metadata, with the aim of making it easier to stop any terrorist attacks and serious crimes from happening.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Legislative metadata has been discussed in various forums, such as workshops held by the Legal Information Institute at the Cornell Law School on 22 and 23 March 2010.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] The documentation for these workshops is titled "Suggested metadata practices for legislation and regulations".
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Australian medical research pioneered the definition of metadata for applications in health care.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] That approach offers the first recognized attempt to adhere to international standards in medical sciences instead of defining a proprietary standard under the World Health Organization (WHO) umbrella.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] The medical community yet did not approve of the need to follow metadata standards despite research that supported these standards.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Research studies in the fields of biomedicine and molecular biology frequently yield large quantities of data, including results of genome or meta-genome sequencing, proteomics data, and even notes or plans created during the course of research itself.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Each data type involves its own variety of metadata and the processes necessary to produce these metadata.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] General metadata standards, such as ISA-Tab, allow researchers to create and exchange experimental metadata in consistent formats.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Specific experimental approaches frequently have their own metadata standards and systems: metadata standards for mass spectrometry include mzML and SPLASH, while XML-based standards such as PDBML and SRA XML serve as standards for macromolecular structure and sequencing data, respectively.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] The products of biomedical research are generally realized as peer-reviewed manuscripts and these publications are yet another source of data .
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] A data warehouse (DW) is a repository of an organization's electronically stored data.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Data warehouses are designed to manage and store the data.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Data warehouses differ from business intelligence (BI) systems because BI systems are designed to use data to create reports and analyze the information, to provide strategic guidance to management.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Metadata is an important tool in how data is stored in data warehouses.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] The purpose of a data warehouse is to house standardized, structured, consistent, integrated, correct, "cleaned" and timely data, extracted from various operational systems in an organization.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] The extracted data are integrated in the data warehouse environment to provide an enterprise-wide perspective.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Data are structured in a way to serve the reporting and analytic requirements.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] The design of structural metadata commonality using a data modeling method such as entity-relationship model diagramming is important in any data warehouse development effort.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] They detail metadata on each piece of data in the data warehouse.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] An essential component of a data warehouse/business intelligence system is the metadata and tools to manage and retrieve the metadata.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Ralph Kimball describes metadata as the DNA of the data warehouse as metadata defines the elements of the data warehouse and how they work together.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Kimball et al. refer to three main categories of metadata: technical, business and process.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Technical metadata is primarily definitional, while business metadata and process metadata are primarily descriptive.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] The HTML format used to define web pages allows for the inclusion of a variety of types of metadata, from basic descriptive text, dates and keywords to further advanced metadata schemes such as the Dublin Core, e-GMS, and AGLS standards.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Pages and files can also be geotagged with coordinates, categorized or tagged, including collaboratively such as with folksonomies.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] When media has identifiers set or when such can be generated, information such as file tags and descriptions can be pulled or scraped from the Internet – for example about movies.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Various online databases are aggregated and provide metadata for various data.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] The collaboratively built Wikidata has identifiers not just for media but also abstract concepts, various objects, and other entities, that can be looked up by humans and machines to retrieve useful information and to link knowledge in other knowledge bases and databases.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Metadata may be included in the page's header or in a separate file.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Microformats allow metadata to be added to on-page data in a way that regular web users do not see, but computers, web crawlers and search engines can readily access.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Many search engines are cautious about using metadata in their ranking algorithms because of exploitation of metadata and the practice of search engine optimization, SEO, to improve rankings.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] See the Meta element article for further discussion.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] This cautious attitude may be justified as people, according to Doctorow, are not executing care and diligence when creating their own metadata and that metadata is part of a competitive environment where the metadata is used to promote the metadata creators own purposes.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Studies show that search engines respond to web pages with metadata implementations, and Google has an announcement on its site showing the meta tags that its search engine understands.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Enterprise search startup Swiftype recognizes metadata as a relevance signal that webmasters can implement for their website-specific search engine, even releasing their own extension, known as Meta Tags 2.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] This metadata can be linked to the video media thanks to the video servers.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Most major broadcast sporting events like FIFA World Cup or the Olympic Games use this metadata to distribute their video content to TV stations through keywords.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] It is often the host broadcaster who is in charge of organizing metadata through its *International Broadcast Centre* and its video servers.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] This metadata is recorded with the images and entered by metadata operators (*loggers*) who associate in live metadata available in *metadata grids* through software (such as Multicam(LSM) or IPDirector used during the FIFA World Cup or Olympic Games).
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Ecological and environmental metadata is intended to document the "who, what, when, where, why, and how" of data collection for a particular study.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] This typically means which organization or institution collected the data, what type of data, which date(s) the data was collected, the rationale for the data collection, and the methodology used for the data collection.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Metadata should be generated in a format commonly used by the most relevant science community, such as Darwin Core, Ecological Metadata Language, or Dublin Core.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Metadata editing tools exist to facilitate metadata generation (e.g.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Metadata should describe the provenance of the data (where they originated, as well as any transformations the data underwent) and how to give credit for (cite) the data products.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] When first released in 1982, Compact Discs only contained a Table Of Contents (TOC) with the number of tracks on the disc and their length in samples.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Fourteen years later in 1996, a revision of the CD Red Book standard added CD-Text to carry additional metadata.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Shortly thereafter, it became common for personal computers to retrieve metadata from external sources (e.g.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Digital audio formats such as digital audio files superseded music formats such as cassette tapes and CDs in the 2000s.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Digital audio files could be labeled with more information than could be contained in just the file name.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] That descriptive information is called the **audio tag** or audio metadata in general.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Computer programs specializing in adding or modifying this information are called tag editors.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Metadata can be used to name, describe, catalog, and indicate ownership or copyright for a digital audio file, and its presence makes it much easier to locate a specific audio file within a group, typically through use of a search engine that accesses the metadata.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] As different digital audio formats were developed, attempts were made to standardize a specific location within the digital files where this information could be stored.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] As a result, almost all digital audio formats, including mp3, broadcast wav, and AIFF files, have similar standardized locations that can be populated with metadata.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] The metadata for compressed and uncompressed digital music is often encoded in the ID3 tag.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Common editors such as TagLib support MP3, Ogg Vorbis, FLAC, MPC, Speex, WavPack TrueAudio, WAV, AIFF, MP4, and ASF file formats.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] With the availability of cloud applications, which include those to add metadata to content, metadata is increasingly available over the Internet.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Metadata can be stored either *internally*, in the same file or structure as the data (this is also called *embedded metadata*), or *externally*, in a separate file or field from the described data.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] A data repository typically stores the metadata *detached* from the data but can be designed to support embedded metadata approaches.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Metadata can be stored in either human-readable or binary form.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Storing metadata in a human-readable format such as XML can be useful because users can understand and edit it without specialized tools.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] However, text-based formats are rarely optimized for storage capacity, communication time, or processing speed.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] A binary metadata format enables efficiency in all these respects, but requires special software to convert the binary information into human-readable content.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Each relational database system has its own mechanisms for storing metadata.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] In database terminology, this set of metadata is referred to as the catalog.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] The SQL standard specifies a uniform means to access the catalog, called the information schema, but not all databases implement it, even if they implement other aspects of the SQL standard.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Programmatic access to metadata is possible using APIs such as JDBC, or SchemaCrawler.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] One of the first satirical examinations of the concept of Metadata as we understand it today is American science fiction author Hal Draper's short story, "MS Fnd in a Lbry" (1961).
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Here, the knowledge of all Mankind is condensed into an object the size of a desk drawer, however, the magnitude of the metadata (e.g. catalog of catalogs of... , as well as indexes and histories) eventually leads to dire yet humorous consequences for the human race.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] The story prefigures the modern consequences of allowing metadata to become more important than the real data it is concerned with, and the risks inherent in that eventuality as a cautionary tale.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Documentation refers to all contextual information that explains and describes a dataset, system, or research process to ensure it is understandable, usable, and reusable.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] It covers broad details such as the study background, data collection methods, file inventories, codebooks, data dictionaries, user guides, and workflow notes.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] In contrast, metadata is a specific and highly structured form of documentation that provides standardized information about the data itself—such as the title, creator, file format, size, access conditions, and how files or sections are organized.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Metadata and documentation are therefore related but distinct concepts in information management.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] Both play crucial roles in data governance, usability, and preservation.
[src:feature-store/metadata-p02] While documentation gives the full narrative and instructions surrounding the data, metadata offers concise, structured descriptors that help users and systems identify, locate, manage and preserve the data efficiently.
